    <pattern>DEALING WITH TOO MUCH WORK</pattern>
    <pattern>WORK TASK PRIORITIZATION</pattern>
    <pattern>WORKLOAD ORGANIZATION</pattern>
    <template>
      Managing your workload is crucial for reducing stress. Here are some tips:
      1. Prioritize tasks and focus on high-priority items first.
      2. Break large projects into smaller, manageable steps.
      3. Set realistic deadlines and communicate them with your team.
      4. Don't hesitate to ask for help when needed.
      5. Learn to say no to additional tasks when your plate is full.
      6. Take regular breaks to prevent burnout.
    </template>
  </category>

  <category>
    <pattern>WORK-LIFE BALANCE</pattern>
    <pattern>HOW TO BALANCE WORK AND LIFE</pattern>
    <pattern>IMPROVING WORK-LIFE BALANCE</pattern>
    <pattern>SETTING BOUNDARIES AT WORK</pattern>
    <pattern>PERSONAL LIFE PRIORITIZATION</pattern>
    <template>
      Achieving work-life balance is essential for reducing stress. Consider these steps:
      1. Set clear boundaries between work and personal life.
      2. Schedule downtime and engage in hobbies or relaxation activities.
      3. Avoid bringing work-related stress home.
      4. Communicate your need for balance with your employer if necessary.
      5. Spend quality time with friends and family.
      Remember, a healthy work-life balance benefits both your well-being and productivity.
    </template>
  </category>

  <category>
    <pattern>WHEN TO SEEK PROFESSIONAL HELP</pattern>
    <pattern>DO I NEED THERAPY FOR STRESS</pattern>
    <pattern>CONSULTING A COUNSELOR FOR STRESS</pattern>
    <pattern>SEEKING HELP FOR WORK-RELATED STRESS</pattern>
    <pattern>THERAPIST FOR JOB STRESS</pattern>
    <template>
      It's important to seek professional help if workplace stress becomes overwhelming. Signs to watch for include:
      1. Persistent anxiety, depression, or mood swings.
      2. Physical symptoms like headaches or sleep disturbances.
      3. Decreased job performance and motivation.
      4. Social withdrawal and isolation.
      5. Substance abuse or excessive use of coping mechanisms.
      If you experience these, consult a mental health professional for support and guidance.
    </template>
